<h1 id="signup">Sign-Up & Sign-in</h1>

<h2>What does it cost?</h2>
<p>Sign-up is free. Anyone can get a free user account.</p>

<h2>How can I remember my password?</h2>
<p>Logosauce can set a cookie so you'll always be logged in or have your password remembered. You can ask your browser to save your login settings.</p>


<h2>I forgot/lost my password - can I reset it?</h2>
<p>Yes - from Sign-in page, click the reset password.</p>
<hr />

<h1 id="logos">Logos</h1>
<h2>Rating & Commenting</h2>

<h3>Who can vote (rate) or comment on a logo ?</h3>
<p>You must be logged in to vote. To login you must have created a free user account(user profile) by <a href="/session/new">signing up</a>.</p>
<br />
<h3>What is the difference between score and ratings and how are they calculated?</h3>
<p>SCORE is made up of the votes cast by users against your logos and earned from other activity such as competition wins. VIEWS are the number of unique page views your logo gallery/detail page has received. Note also that votes by qiualified users such as "Pro" designers, clients, etc are worth more to your overall score.
</p>
<br />

<h2>How is score calculated?</h2>
<p>Score = votes.  Score is calculated as follows.
 <ul>
<h3>Vote cast by a standard user</h3>
<li>1 bottle is worth 1 point.</li>
<li>2 bottles is worth 2 points</li>
<li>3 bottles is worth 3 points.</li>
</ul>
 
Simple enough. However these votes are multiplied by 3 if the vote is cast by a Pro Designer. 

<ul>
<h3>Vote cast by a Pro Designer</h3>
<li>1 bottle is worth 3 points.</li>
<li>2 bottles is worth 6 points</li>
<li>3 bottles is worth 9 points.</li>
</ul>
Votes by a client in his/her own competition are worth 10 times. 

<ul>
<h3>Vote cast by a Client in own competition</h3>
<li>1 bottle is worth 10 points.</li>
<li>2 bottles is worth 20 points</li>
<li>3 bottles is worth 30 points.</li>
</ul>
</p>
<p>And there are additional points awarded as follows</p>
<ul>
<li>Competition win is worth 100 points</li>
<li>Winning project bid is worth 100 points</li>
</ul>

<p>While a user can comment multiple time a user can only vote once per logo. A user may also change his/her vote.</p>

<h2>What is the Favourites number?</h2>
<p>Favourites is the number of users who have added this logo to their favourites list. You must be logged in to add to favourites.</p>
  
<h2>Searching & Viewing</h2>

<h3>How does search work?</h3>
<p>Search in Logosauce has kept as simple as possible. <br /><br />Each Tab has it's own special search. Click on the Logos tab and then use the search box to search for logos. On the people tab use the search box to search for people. Search by default looks at Item name (e.g. logo, person, company etc), Notes and Tags and display these sorted by published date (most recent first).</p>
<br />
<h3>How do I view logo detail and a larger image?</h3>
<p>Search for the Logo you want - click on the thumbnail image to view the Gallery/Detail page. then click the logo again to view the Lightbox image which displays the logo with all the background detail blacked out.</p>
<br />
<h3>How can I access original or source artwork?</h3>
<p>Logosauce does not store source artwork. However designers may add information about where you can find the source artwork for the logo they have listed. If the information is provided - it can be found on the gallery/detail page of each logo. Failing that you can contact the user who published the logo by checking out the users profile.<br /><br />The exception to this is for Design Competition where the winning design source artwork is uploaded for the client to retrieve. This artwork is only available to the paying client and competition owner.</p>
<br />
<h2 id="finalart">Final Art Files</h2>
 <p>If you're supplying logo artwork to a client - either as the result of winning a competition or otherwise, your artwork files should comply with the following standards.</p>
 <ul>
   <li>You should generally be supplying any logo artwork in a vector format. Raster based artwork is rarely suitable for logo artwork.</li>
   <li>Preferred vector format is Adobe Illustrator .ai or Adobe Illustrator .eps file formats.</li>
   <li>Please save any Illustrator or other Adobe Creative suite files with the CS suite edition set to one or two versions lower than the current CS version. This will ensure compatibility for clients with older versions of software.</li>
   <li>Ensure that when saving .eps files you select 8bit Tiff previews for your files (not Mac preview).</li>
   <li>Ensure all fonts are pathed (converted to outlines) before saving.</li>
   <li>You should save and upload a separate file for each colour-space that you have generated - such as SPOT, CMYK, RGB, etc.</li>
   <li>If you have multiple files to upload - please zip them first and upload the zip file.</li>
   </ul>



